<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06228177 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06228177 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  FRANCE; FINANCE; PROFESSIONAL; SALE; SPORT; FASHION; COMPANY  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  Flamboyant French financier Bernard Tapie announced that he will sell a 45percent stake in the company that controls sporting-goods giant Adidas to payloans used to buy the German firm last year.;    Tapie purchased 95 percent ofAdidas last year through a German holding, Bernard Tapie Finance Gmbh.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Business  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  TAPIE TO SELL 45% OF ADIDAS TO PAY LOANSUSED FOR BUY  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     The Paris-based Bernard Tapie Finance SA announced that Tapie will reducehis 100 percent stake in the German unit to 55 percent and sell 45 percent tovarious investors.;    The sale will leave Tapie as majority stockholder inthe athletic-shoe and apparel firm founded by Adi Dassler, which remains bestknown for shoes with three trademarked stripes.;    Pentland Group PLC, aclothing firm based in Scotland, will buy 20.05 percent of Bernard Tapie Gmbh,while 19.95 percent will go to French institutional investors and 5 percent toAdidas management.;    The French investors are the state-owned bank CreditLyonnais, state-controlled insurer Assurances Generales de France and theprivate Banque Worms.;    Chairman Stephen Rubin of Pentland said that theAdidas brand name had been underutilized and he hopes the new partners canhelp expand sales.;    Pentland will pay $78.2 million for its stake, and hasan option to buy 5 percent more from one of the French institutions, Rubinsaid.;    The option can be exercised between 1993 and 1996 for $27.9 millionto $55.8 million, depending on developments at Adidas.;    Under the terms ofthe option, Pentland will have 25.05 percent, the French institutions 9.95percent, management 10 percent and Tapie Finance will retain 55 percent, TapieFinance said.;    The sale was expected following word from Tapie in June thathe was prepared to sell as much as 45 percent of Bernard Tapie Finance Gmbh torepay creditors.;    Tapie acquired his Adidas stake in two parts, mostly fromthe Dassler family. Analysts predicted the venture was risky, noting that thesportswear market presents little possibility for expansion and is saturatedwith competitors.;    Bernard Tapie Finance Gmbh paid $272 million for 80percent of Adidas, and later bought another 15 percent for $68 million.;   German and French banks financed the first investment with one- and two-yearloans. Tapie faces a first payment of $102 million.;    Bernard Tapie FinanceSA said the capital reorganization will permit it to pay $215 million tocreditors, but it wasn't clear over how long.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Associated Press  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><CITY>  Paris  </CITY><EDITION>  Street  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910815  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Thursday  </DAY><MONTH>  August  </MONTH><PG.COL>  8F  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  391  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Thursday August 15, 199100228177,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>